Resampling¶

Resampling involves changing the frequency of the time series observations.

Two types of resampling are:

Upsampling: Where we increase the frequency of the samples, such as from minutes to seconds.

Downsampling: Where we decrease the frequency of the samples, such as from days to months.

In [430]:
# We can resample with daily frequency but the output is quite ununderstandable. 
# I chosed to downsample the resampling as monthly to have a better 'human' point of view
resample_weekly = temp.resample('M')
monthly_frequency = resample_weekly.mean()
monthly_frequency.plot(figsize = (16, 5))
plt.title("Monthly frequency of the daily temperature in Melbourne, Australia")
plt.show()
#len(monthly_frequency)

If we set the resampling to a monthly frequency, we can see that the there is a seasonality. Obviously, the seasonality is linked to the seasons in Australia, They highest daily temperatures occur during the begining of the year in january with 16°, then drop down in June with a daily temperature of 8° wich tend to correspond to what can be found on internet

From now on, monthly_frequency is the dataset we are working with

monthly_frequency['Daily temp'] is the resampled dataframe of temp['Daily temp']

monthly_frequency and temp are both df

We can deduce that the model is additive¶

Testing the stationarity¶

Import the augmented Dickey-Fuller test from the statsmodels package¶

It is from the test statistic and the p-value that we can determine whether a given series is stationary or not. We use the following null and alternative hypotheses:

H0: The time searies is not stationary.

H1: The time series is stationary.

We compute several test to determine if the model is stationary in every cases : The existing trend can hide its non stationarity : We verify if Test Statistics < critical value, meaning that p-value < 5% with the following cases :

  • we include a constant
  • we include a trend
In [432]:
from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller
#  Pass our data frame into the adfuller method. 

 # constant
adft_c = adfuller(monthly_frequency,autolag=None,regression='c')

output_df_c = pd.DataFrame({"Values":[adft_c[0],adft_c[1],adft_c[4]['1%'], adft_c[4]['5%'], adft_c[4]['10%']]  , "Metric":["Test Statistics","p-value", 
                                                        "critical value (1%)", "critical value (5%)", "critical value (10%)"]})
print(output_df_c)

# Our data is stationary : the test statistic < critical value, donc p-value < 5% 
  
print()

adft_ct = adfuller(monthly_frequency,autolag=None,regression='ct')#, store=True)

Determine if data is seasonal¶

The common way to test for seasonality of a time series is to plot the series and check for repeatable patterns in fixed time intervals. So, the types of seasonality is determined by the year calendar.

However, if we want a more definitive inspection of the seasonality, we use the Autocorrelation Function (ACF) plot. There is a strong seasonal pattern, the ACF plot usually reveals definitive repeated spikes at the multiples of the seasonal window.

In [434]:
# Test for seasonality

Detrend¶

Before forecasting, we remove the trend to the model by importing diff or by substracting the rolling mean from the dataset to get the detrended time series

In [436]:
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.tools import diff
plt.figure(figsize = (16, 5))

# With diff :
monthly_frequency_detrended = diff(monthly_frequency)
plt.plot(monthly_frequency_detrended, color='darkturquoise', label="With diff method")

# With rolling mean :

rolling_mean = monthly_frequency.rolling(4).mean()
monthly_frequency_detrended_rm = monthly_frequency - rolling_mean
plt.plot(monthly_frequency_detrended_rm, color='orangered',label="With rolling mean method")
plt.title("monthly_frequency detrended ")
plt.legend(loc="best")
plt.show()

Autocorrelation and Partial Autocorrelation Functions¶

Autocorrelation is simply the correlation of a series with its own lags. If a series is significantly autocorrelated, so the previous values of the series (lags) may be helpful in predicting the current value.

Partial Autocorrelation also conveys similar information but it conveys the pure correlation of a series and its lag, excluding the correlation contributions from the intermediate lags.

We need to do the correlation on detrended model¶
